raw._content: SrA Mark Stimmler, a member of the 7EMS, .Structural Maintenance shop, carefully places the bottom half of the 911 commemorative nose art on a B-1B Lancer from the 9th Bomb Squadron, Dyess AFB, TX, 15 Feb 02.USAF photo: SSgt Tracy Reisinger..DYESS AIR FORCE BASE, Texas (ACCNS) -- A B-1 here joined other Air Force aircraft in representing the spirit of 9-11 when it was given the honor of bearing the Air Force’s “Let’s Roll!” nose art Feb. 15..Todd Beamer, a passenger on Flight 93, made the phrase “Let’s roll!” famous when he and other passengers rushed terrorists for control of the aircraft before it crashed into a field in western Pennsylvania. He was overheard on a cellular phone reciting the Lord’s Prayer and saying, “Let’s roll!” before the rush...“‘Let’s roll!’ has served as a rallying cry for this nation as we go forward in our war on terrorism,” said Air Force Chief of Staff Gen. John P. Jumper. “We are proud to display this new nose art on our aircraft.”
